04496nam a22007695i 9789814695244DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898146952447 a10.1355/97898146952442doi  a(DE-B1597)522142  a(OCoLC)1100447895  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aSOC0070002bisacsh1 aFarrelly , Nicholas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEstablishing Contemporary Chinese Life in Myanmar /cOlinga-Shannon Stephanie, Nicholas Farrelly. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (29 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tEstablishing Contemporary Chinese Life in Myanmar -- tEstablishing Contemporary Chinese Life in Myanmar -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom 1985 the Chinese government adopted a proactive policy of engaging with Myanmar and encouraged its people to do the same. China has thus played a major role in Myanmar's recent evolution, especially with respect to the number of its citizens and former citizens living in the country and working to transform its economy. A long, porous border unites Myanmar and China and serves as "back door" to both countries. It is through this land border that Myanmar and China face one another. This contrasts with Western countries that have tended to view both China and Myanmar from the vantage of the sea. From state investment in billion dollar projects to the small shop owners in every village and town in northern Myanmar, the Chinese have entangled themselves in all levels of the Myanmar economy. Ethnic Chinese living in Myanmar are well aware that they are permanent outsiders in Myanmar society, even if their families have lived there for generations. The dichotomy persists between "Chinese" and "locals" and is reinforced through discriminatory laws, media and popular culture. The long-term situation of the Chinese in Myanmar remains profoundly unclear. Many of them appear to have determined that Myanmar will continue to be part of their plans, but that they are also seeking to remain mobile, able to seize new opportunities where they emerge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChina—Foreign economic relations—Myanmar. 0aChinese—Myanmar. 0aEmigration & Immigration. 0aMyanmar—Foreign economic relations—China. 0aMyanmar—Foreign relations—China. 4aEmigration & Immigration. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aStephanie, Olinga-Shannon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981469524440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814695244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814695244.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK